          {
            "text": "Build and cook",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the {{mushrooms-chestnut}}, {{mushrooms-portobello}}, {{onion}}, {{garlic}}, {{dijon-mustard}}, {{smoked-paprika}}, {{tomato-puree}}, {{soy-sauce-light}}, {{sea-salt-fine}}, and {{black-pepper}} to the slow cooker. Pour over the {{stock-vegetable}} and stir to combine. Cook on low for 4 hours, until the mushrooms are tender and the sauce is deep and well-seasoned. Switch off. Wait 5 minutes, then stir through the {{soured-cream}} until smooth. Taste and adjust seasoning. Serve immediately.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Always wait until the pot is fully off and has cooled slightly. Full-fat soured cream is more stable than low-fat. Stir gently rather than vigorously",
              "cause": "Added to a pot that was still simmering",
              "symptom": "Soured cream has split into grainy curds"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid and cook on high for 15 to 20 minutes to reduce before adding the soured cream",
              "cause": "Mushrooms released a lot of water",
              "symptom": "Sauce very watery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Continue for another 30 to 60 minutes. Mushrooms should be completely yielding and soft, having collapsed and concentrated",
              "cause": "Undercooked, or the cooker runs cool",
              "symptom": "Mushrooms rubbery rather than tender"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Mushroom stroganoff is a quick-to-build vegetarian weeknight dinner. The four-hour cook time is the shortest in the slow-cooker savoury section. Serve over rice or egg noodles with a green salad. The soy sauce provides the depth that Worcestershire sauce would in the meat version, without the anchovies.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
